{"title_page": "Emily Thornberry", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = Emily Thornberry\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Emily Thornberry MP crop 2.jpg\n|caption = Thornberry in January 2020\n|office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade|Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]\n|leader = [[Keir Starmer]]\n|term_start = 6 April 2020\n|predecessor = [[Barry Gardiner]]\n|office1 = [[Shadow First Secretary of State]]\n|leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start1 = 14 June 2017\n|term_end1 = 5 April 2020\n|predecessor1 = [[Angela Eagle]] (2016)\n|successor1  = [[Angela Rayner]]\n|office2 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]\n|leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start2 = 27 June 2016\n|term_end2 = 5 April 2020\n|predecessor2 = [[Hilary Benn]]\n|successor2 = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n|office3 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n|leader3 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start3 = 20 July 2016\n|term_end3 = 6 October 2016\n|predecessor3 = ''Position established''\n|successor3 = [[Keir Starmer]]\n|office4 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence]]\n|leader4 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start4 = 5 January 2016\n|term_end4 = 27 June 2016\n|predecessor4 = [[Maria Eagle]]\n|successor4 = [[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]]\n|office5 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow Minister of State for Employment]]\n|leader5 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start5 = 16 September 2015\n|term_end5 = 6 January 2016\n|predecessor5 = [[Stephen Timms]]\n|successor5 = [[Nick Thomas-Symonds]]\n|office6 = [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]]\n|leader6 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start6 = 7 October 2011\n|term_end6 = 3 December 2014\n|predecessor6 = [[Patricia Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal|The Baroness Scotland of Asthal]]\n|successor6 = [[Willy Bach, Baron Bach|The Lord Bach]]\n|office8 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]]\n|term_start8 = 6 May 2005\n|term_end8 =\n|predecessor8 = [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]]\n|successor8 = \n|majority8 = 17,328 (36.3%)\n|birth_name=Emily Anne Thornberry\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1960|7|27}}\n|birth_place = [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]], England\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Christopher Nugee]]|July 1991}}\n|children = 3\n|parents = [[Cedric Thornberry]]<br />Sallie Thornberry\n|alma_mater = [[University of Kent]]\n|website = {{official|emilythornberry.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Emily Anne Thornberry''' (born 27 July 1960) is a [[British people|British]] [[politician]] who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]] since [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], she served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Shadow First Secretary of State]] from 2017 to 2020 and [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]] from 2016 to 2020. \n\nThornberry practised as a [[barrister]] from 1985 to 2005. She was first elected to Parliament in 2005, and served as [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]] in [[Ed Miliband]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband|shadow cabinet]] from 2011 until she resigned in 2014 after sending a tweet that was described as \"snobby\". After [[Jeremy Corbyn]] won the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 leadership election]], Thornberry was appointed [[Department for Work and Pensions|shadow employment minister]]. In [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn#January 2016 reshuffle|January 2016]], she was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence|Shadow Defence Secretary]], and in [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn#June 2016 reshuffle|June 2016]] she was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]]. She was a candidate to succeed [[Jeremy Corbyn|Corbyn]] as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]] in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020 leadership election]]. She was appointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet of Keir Starmer]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade|Shadow International Trade Secretary]] in April 2020, succeeding [[Barry Gardiner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/press/keir-starmer-announces-senior-shadow-cabinet-appointments/|title=Keir Starmer announces senior Shadow Cabinet appointments|website=[[The Labour Party (UK)| The Labour Party]]|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThornberry was born in [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]] on 27 July 1960.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-45759|title=Thornberry, Rt Hon. Emily, (born 27 July 1960), PC 2016; MP (Lab) Islington South and Finsbury, since 2005 {{!}} WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO|website=www.ukwhoswho.com|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U45759|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a3055464-b54f-11e8-bbc3-ccd7de085ffe|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> Her parents were Sallie Thornberry, a teacher, and [[Cedric Thornberry]], at the time teaching international law at the [[London School of Economics]], and later a [[Assistant Secretary-General|United Nations Assistant Secretary-General]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/21/emily-thornberry-profile-labour-mp-islington|title=Emily Thornberry: Guildford girl who went on to become a devoted MP|last=Johnston|first=Chris|date=21 November 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iww8h3E8MBMC&pg=PA719&lpg=PA719&dq=cederic+thornberry+UN+nato#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The UN Security Council: From the Cold War to the 21st Century \u2013 David Malone |accessdate=20 June 2012|isbn=9781588262400 |last1=Malone |first1=David |last2=Malone |first2=Rector David M. |year=2004 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/01/cedric-thornberry|title=Cedric Thornberry obituary|last=Ahtisaari|first=Martti|date=1 June 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> When Thornberry was seven, her parents divorced and she had to leave their home with her mother and two brothers. After this, she relied on free school meals and food parcels, and their cats were euthanised to save money.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/25/emily-thornberry-labour-hope-have-election|title=Emily Thornberry: 'I hope we have an election before any more damage is done'|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|date=25 November 2017|website=The Guardian|accessdate=}}</ref> Her mother later became a Labour [[councillor]] and mayor, and her father stood as the Labour candidate for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] in the [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966 general election]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Aida | last=Edemariam | title=Right, so just what do you do all day? | date=19 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nShe failed the [[eleven-plus]] exam, so attended a [[secondary modern school]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She left to live with her father when she was fifteen until he left without warning to work for the [[United Nations]] when she was seventeen. She worked as a cleaner and a barmaid in London alongside resitting her [[O-Levels]] and taking her [[A-Levels]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/21/emily-thornberry-interview-labour-antisemitism-brexit-chippy|title=Emily Thornberry: 'Being chippy is a good thing'|last=Cooke|first=Rachel|date=21 July 2019|work=The Observer|accessdate=21 July 2019|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> She went on to study law at the [[University of Kent]] in [[Canterbury]], graduating in 1982. She was called to the Bar at [[Gray's Inn]] and practised as a barrister specialising in human rights law from 1985 to 2005 under [[Michael Mansfield]] at Tooks Chambers.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThornberry joined the [[Transport and General Workers' Union]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XhMWAQAAIAAJ&q=%22emily+thornberry%22+1960&dq=%22emily+thornberry%22+1960 |title=Dod's parliamentary companion guide to the general election, 2005 \u2013 Valerie Passmore, David Roe |accessdate=20 June 2012|isbn=9780905702575 |last1=Passmore |first1=Valerie |year=2005 }}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Before Parliament ===\nIn the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], she stood as the Labour candidate in [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]], but was defeated by the Conservative incumbent, [[Julian Brazier]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/constituency/788/canterbury|title=Canterbury: Constituency|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 June 2012|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the decision of [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]] not to stand again, Thornberry was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]] for the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] through an [[All-women shortlists|all-women shortlist]] of prospective candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf|title=Standard Note SN/PC/05057|work=House of Commons Library|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618162209/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf|archivedate=18 June 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref> She was elected to Parliament with a majority of 484.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/341.stm|title=Election 2005 \u2013 Islington South & Finsbury|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> [[Nick Smith (British politician)|Nick Smith]] (who subsequently was elected to Parliament representing [[Blaenau Gwent (UK Parliament constituency)|Blaenau Gwent]]) served as her election agent.\n\n===Early Parliamentary career (2005\u20132010)===\nThornberry made her [[maiden speech]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 24 May 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo050524/debtext/50524-26.htm#50524-26_spnew0 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 24 May 2005 (pt 26) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=24 May 2005 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> In Parliament, she has been a member of the Environmental Audit Committee and was on the [[Communities and Local Government Committee|Communities and Local Government Select Committee]] during the 2005\u201310 Parliament. She has served as vice-chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Cycling Group and the All-Party Parliamentary Pro-Choice and Sexual Health Group.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn 2006, Thornberry was criticised by the Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards [[Philip Mawer]] for adding a quote from herself into a news release by the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]]. She was found not to have broken the Parliamentary code of conduct.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7062530.stm|title=MP 'unwise' to alter news release|date=29 October 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThornberry's main interests since becoming an MP have been in health, housing, the environment and equality.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-35234485|title=Emily Thornberry: Comeback queen|last=Wheeler|first=Brian|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> She has also spoken on the need for more affordable housing, particularly in [[Islington]]. In 2006, Thornberry introduced the Housing Association Bill, a [[Private Member's Bill]] which sought to improve the control of housing association tenants over their landlords.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmbills/035/07035.i-5.html |title=Housing Association (Rights and Representation of Residents) Bill |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=28 February 2007 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Many of the ideas from this bill were taken up by the Cave Review.<ref>[http://www.communities.gov.uk/housing/strategiesandreviews/cavereview1 Cave Review] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081114124338/http://www.communities.gov.uk/housing/strategiesandreviews/cavereview1 |date=14 November 2008 }}</ref> On environmental matters, Thornberry worked with [[Friends of the Earth]] and [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) to campaign for a Climate Change Bill and a Marine Bill. In 2006, Thornberry won the ePolitix Award for Environment Champion of the Year after being nominated by WWF.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ecca.org.uk/charity_champion_award_2006.doc |accessdate=18 November 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Thornberry supported a change in the law to allow single women and lesbian couples to seek [[in vitro fertilisation]] treatment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7410934.stm|title=MPs reject need for father in IVF|date=20 May 2008|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/fertility-laws-drop-need-to-consider-role-of-father-831544.html|title=Fertility laws drop need to consider role of father|date=21 May 2008|website=The Independent|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she was appointed as a ministerial aide in the [[Department of Energy and Climate Change]] and attended the [[Copenhagen Summit]] in December that year with [[Joan Ruddock]] and [[Ed Miliband]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/news/2010/09/28/climate-change-deal-several-years-away|title=Climate change deal 'several years away'|website=politics.co.uk|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition under Ed Miliband (2010\u20132015)===\n{{See also|Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband}}\nIn May 2010, Thornberry was returned as MP for Islington South and Finsbury with an increased majority, in a seat identified as the Liberal Democrats' top target in England for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/may/election-2010-results-emily-wins-night-jubilant-emily-thornberry-defeats-lib-dem-bridg|title=Jubilant Emily Thornberry defeats Lib Dem Bridget Fox in Islington South & Finsbury|date=7 May 2010|work=Islington Tribune|accessdate=20 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317111337/http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/may/election-2010-results-emily-wins-night-jubilant-emily-thornberry-defeats-lib-dem-bridg|archivedate=17 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/15731364 |title=Election campaigning: A tale of two constituencies |work=The Economist |date= 20 March 2010|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThornberry was promoted to Shadow Minister for the Department of Energy and Climate Change in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/emily-thornberry/1536|title=Emily Thornberry MP|publisher=Parliament UK|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In the role she shadowed [[Charles Hendry]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons, Westminster |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm100708/halltext/100708h0001.htm#10070873000191 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 8 July 2010 (pt 0001) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Thornberry missed out on a place in Labour's [[Shadow Cabinet|shadow cabinet]], then elected by Labour MPs, by one vote. She was instead promoted to the role of shadow care minister under the shadow health secretary [[John Healey (politician)|John Healey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/news/new_job_cheers_mp_emily_thornberry_after_shadow_cabinet_heartbreak_1_682213 |title=New job cheers MP Emily Thornberry after shadow cabinet heartbreak  |work=Islington Gazette |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/oct/emily-thornberry-set-shadow-every-coalition-move-health |title=Emily Thornberry set to shadow every Coalition move on health |work=Islington Tribune |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303120348/http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/oct/emily-thornberry-set-shadow-every-coalition-move-health |archivedate=3 March 2012  }}</ref>\n\nAs shadow care minister, Thornberry criticised the coalition government's lack of action over failing care home operator Southern Cross, calling for action and that the government put in place a plan B should the operator fail.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/uk-13611766 |title= Southern Cross: Government tries to reassure residents |publisher= BBC News|date= 1 June 2011|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> She criticised the government over the Winterborne View care home abuse scandal, calling for an investigation into the affair.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/jun/07/ed-miliband-talks-future-social-care |title=Government could order independent inquiry into Winterbourne View|work=The Guardian |date=7 June 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |location=London |first=Helene |last=Mulholland}}</ref> In April 2011, Thornberry surveyed all the local government directors of adult social care and highlighted the pressures on care for the elderly by the coalition government's cuts to local authority funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coalitionwatch.info/2011/04/crisis-of-care-predicted-by-labour.html |title=Coalition watch |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129095502/http://www.coalitionwatch.info/2011/04/crisis-of-care-predicted-by-labour.html |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThornberry was appointed [[Shadow Attorney General|shadow attorney general]] in October 2011, in which capacity she attended shadow cabinet meetings.<ref name=\"parliament1\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201212/cmhansrd/cm120320/debtext/120320-0001.htm#12032051001266 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 20 Mar 2012 (pt 0001) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Thornberry called for action by [[Dominic Grieve]] over [[Applied Language Solutions]]' failure to provide interpreters for court proceedings,<ref>{{cite news|first=Owen |last=Bowcott|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2012/mar/19/private-court-interpretation-contractor-contempt |title=Private court interpretation company 'should face contempt proceedings |work=The Guardian |date= 19 March 2012|accessdate=20 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref> and called on the attorney general to ensure that allegations of bribery involving [[Bernie Ecclestone]] were properly investigated.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn 2011, Thornberry challenged [[David Cameron]] over his false claims about wages at Islington Council,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2011/jul/still-no-apology-prime-minister-david-cameron-salary-%E2%80%98lie%E2%80%99 |title=Still no apology from Prime Minister David Cameron for salary 'lie' |work=Camden New Journal |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111024523/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2011/jul/still-no-apology-prime-minister-david-cameron-salary-%E2%80%98lie%E2%80%99 |archivedate=11 January 2016  }}</ref> campaigning against government measures which Thornberry claimed to have exacerbated child poverty in Islington,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emilythornberry.com/news/53/17/New-figures-reveal-Islington-suffers-second-worst-child-poverty-in-the-UK |title=News Emily Thornberry is the Labour MP for Islington South & Finsbury and Shadow Health & Social Care Minister |publisher=emilythornberry.com |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219070849/http://www.emilythornberry.com/news/53/17/New-figures-reveal-Islington-suffers-second-worst-child-poverty-in-the-UK |archivedate=19 February 2012 }}</ref> and answering over 1,000 enquiries a month from constituents.<ref name=\"Edemariam\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Aida | last=Edemariam | title=Right, so just what do you do all day? | date=19 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nThornberry resigned her shadow cabinet position on 20 November 2014, shortly after polls closed in the [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|Rochester and Strood by-election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30139832|title=Labour's Emily Thornberry quits over 'snobby' tweet|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/20/emily-thornberry-resigns-rochester-tweet-labour-shadow-cabinet|title=Emily Thornberry resigns from shadow cabinet over Rochester tweet|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2014}}</ref> Earlier in the day, she had received criticism after [[tweeting]] a photograph of a house in the constituency adorned with three [[Flag of England|flags of St. George]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30139832 |title=Labour's Emily Thornberry quits over 'snobby' tweet \u2013 BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=21 November 2014 |accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> and the owner's [[white van man|white van]] parked outside on the driveway, under the caption \"Image from #Rochester\", provoking accusations of [[snob]]bery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30139832|title=Labour's Emily Thornberry quits over tweet|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 November 2014 |publisher=BBC News | accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> She was criticised by fellow Labour Party MPs, including leader [[Ed Miliband]] who said her tweet conveyed a \"sense of disrespect\", [[Chris Bryant]] who said that it broke the \"first rule of politics\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30148768|title=Miliband: Thornberry's 'white van, flag' tweet lacked respect|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> and [[Simon Danczuk]] who said that the party had been \"hijacked by the north London [[liberal elite]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30142579|title=Emily Thornberry: How one tweet led to her resignation|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition under Jeremy Corbyn (2015\u20132020)===\n{{See also|Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn}}\n[[File:Emily Thornberry, 2016 Labour Party Conference 2.jpg|thumb|Thornberry giving her Shadow Foreign Secretary speech at the 2016 Labour Party Conference]]\nIn September 2015, she was appointed as the shadow minister for employment by the new Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\":4\" /> She was promoted to shadow defence secretary in January 2016, replacing [[Maria Eagle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jan/05/hilary-benn-expected-to-keep-his-job-as-corbyn-finishes-shadow-cabinet-reshuffle-politics-live|title=Emily Thornberry named Shadoecretary in Labour reshuffle|last1=Sparrow|first1=Andrew|date=6 January 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Thornberry advocated spending money on the army rather than on the UK's [[Trident (UK nuclear programme)|Trident]] nuclear programme.<ref name=\":4\" /> On being appointed, Thornberry was interviewed by the [[British Forces Broadcasting Service]], where she defended her appointment, saying she had \"quite a lot more experience than people might think.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35248233 |title=Emily Thornberry defends Labour defence appointment |publisher=BBC News |date=6 January 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> During her role as shadow defence secretary, Thornberry conducted a review of defence policy, including the role of the nuclear deterrent, which was delayed following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jan/14/emily-thornberry-final-say-labour-trident-review-nuclear-ken-livingstone|title=Emily Thornberry will have final say on Labour's Trident review|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=14 January 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> During a private Labour discussion about the nuclear deterrent, Thornberry asked what \"[[DEFCON|Defcon]] One\", a status of the United States nuclear defence rating, meant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/03/labours-shadow-defence-secretary-does-not-understand-what-defcon/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Labour's shadow defence secretary 'does not understand what Defcon One means'|accessdate=15 September 2016|date=3 April 2016 |last1=Riley-Smith |first1=Ben }}</ref>\n\nThornberry was promoted to [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]] in June 2016 after Corbyn fired [[Hilary Benn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-36632956|title=Jeremy Corbyn unveils new top team after resignations|date=27 June 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> She held the role of [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow Brexit Secretary]] concurrently until [[Keir Starmer]] took on the role later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/the1000/the-progress-1000-londons-most-influential-people-2016-westminster-a3336621.html|title=The Progress 1000: Westminster|date=7 September 2016|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> She accused Sky News presenter [[Dermot Murnaghan]] of sexism after he asked her to name French [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Development (France)|minister of foreign affairs and international development]], [[Jean-Marc Ayrault]] and the president of South Korea, which she was unable to do.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37332287|title=Thornberry accuses presenter of 'sexism'|date=11 September 2016|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/11/emily-thornberry-sexism-dermot-murnaghan-sky-news|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Sky presenter Murnaghan of sexism|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|date=11 September 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/11/emily-thornberry-accuses-sky-news-presenter-of-sexism-after-fail/|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Sky News presenter Dermot Murnaghan of 'sexism' after failing to name French foreign minister|last=Hughes|first=Laura|date=11 September 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Following the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], she was given the additional role of [[Shadow First Secretary of State|Shadow First Secretary of State]], effectively acting as Corbyn's number 2. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/emily-thornberry-interview-i-do-have-a-go-at-boris-weve-lost-status-people-laugh-at-us-now-ff6056d5z|title=Emily Thornberry interview: 'I do have a go at Boris. We've lost status \u2014 people laugh at us now'|last=Fisher|first=Lucy|date=23 December 2017|work=The Times|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nThornberry opposed Britain's involvement in the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]] against the [[Shia]] [[Houthis]]. She said that \"while Saudi Arabia will remain a valued [[Saudi Arabia\u2013United Kingdom relations|strategic, security and economic ally]] in the years to come, our support for their forces in Yemen must be suspended until the alleged violations of international humanitarian law in that conflict have been fully and independently investigated.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour MPs face backlash over failure to vote on Yemen campaign |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/27/labour-mps-face-backlash-over-failure-to-vote-on-yemen-campaign |last=Mason |first=Rowena |work=The Guardian |date=27 October 2016}}</ref> In May 2018 Thornberry said support in [[Syria]] for the country's president, [[Bashar al-Assad]], had been \u201cunderestimated\u201d in the West.<ref>{{cite web|first=Samuel |last=Osborne |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/assad-syria-emily-thornberry-support-underestimated-jeremy-corbyn-russia-a8355241.html |title=Emily Thornberry claims public support for Syria's Bashar al-Assad has been 'underestimated' |work=The Independent |date= 17 May 2018|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Foster |first=Matt |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/world/middle-east/news/95218/emily-thornberry-bashar-al-assads-popularity-syria-has-been |title=Emily Thornberry: Bashar al-Assad's popularity in Syria has been 'underestimated' |publisher=PoliticsHome.com |date=16 May 2018|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> In October 2018 Thornberry criticised [[Theresa May]]'s government's response to [[Jamal Khashoggi]]'s disappearance as \"too little, too late\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi: Labour slams government's response as 'too little, too late'. |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/13/labour-slams-government-over-khashoggi-response-emily-thornberry |last=Graham-Harrison |first=Emma |work=The Guardian |date=13 October 2018}}</ref> She said: \"Imagine how this government would have reacted if either Russia or Iran had abducted\u2013and in all likelihood murdered\u2013one of their dissident journalists within the sovereign territory of another country.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=European Governments Wrestle with Khashoggi Quandary |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/european-governments-wrestle-with-khashoggi-quandary/4617229.html |work=VOA News |date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Corbyn announced he was stepping down as leader, Thornberry was the first person to officially announce that she would be running for leader of the Labour Party, in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020 leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/thornberry-first-to-enter-labour-leadership-race-after-election-defeat|title=Thornberry first to enter Labour leadership race after election defeat|last=Bates|first=Liz|website=Channel 4 News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the week after the election, defeated Labour MP [[Caroline Flint]] appeared on ''[[Sophy Ridge on Sunday]]'' and accused Thornberry of saying that Brexit voters in [[Northern England]] were 'stupid'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/|title=Yorkshire Post - Yorkshire News|website=Yorkshire Post|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Thornberry appeared on [[ITV News|''ITV News'']] and accused Flint of 'making up shit about her' and threatened to take [[legal action]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-15/thornberry-criticises-total-and-utter-lie-shared-by-labour-colleague/|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Caroline Flint of 'making up s***' about her and says she is taking legal action|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/16/emily-thornberry-threatens-to-sue-over-caroline-flint-stupid-voters-claim|title=Emily Thornberry threatens to sue over 'stupid voters' claim|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=2019-12-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She was eventually eliminated from the leadership election after failing to achieve enough nominations from the party's MPs and MEPs.\n\nAfter the killing of [[Qasem Soleimani]] in the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike]], Thornberry condemned the actions of the [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]]. She said that she shed no tears over the death, but was fearful of escalating tensions in the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/05/boris-johnson-qassem-suleimani-was-threat-to-all-our-interests-lament-death|title=Boris Johnson: Qassem Suleimani was threat to all our interests|last=editor|first=Heather Stewart Political|date=2020-01-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition under Keir Starmer (2020\u2013present)===\n{{See also|Shadow Cabinet of Keir Starmer}}\nThornberry was replaced as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]] by [[Lisa Nandy]] upon the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|election]] of [[Keir Starmer]] as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52175841|title=Lisa Nandy appointed shadow foreign secretary|date=2020-04-05|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/indianorigin-british-mp-lisa-nandy-promises-constructive-opposition-as-uk-shadow-minister/1793588|title=Indian-origin British MP Lisa Nandy promises constructive Opposition as UK shadow minister|last=|first=|date=|website=outlookindia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Thornberry herself was not sacked from the [[Official Opposition frontbench]], but instead moved to a lower-ranking frontbench role, becoming the new [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]. She replaced [[Barry Gardiner]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/news/emily-thornberry-appointed-as-shadow-international-trade-secretary-1-6595958|title=Emily Thornberry appointed as shadow international trade secretary|last=Cumiskey|first=Lucas|website=Islington Gazette|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and said on [[Twitter]] that, \"It's been a pleasure to work with Barry Gardiner these past four years... I hope I can take the fight to the government on [[International trade|International Trade]] as effectively as he did, and I'll be very lucky to have his advice\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://islingtontribune.com/article/emily-thornberry-appointed-international-trade-secretary-in-keir-starmer-shadow-cabinet|title=Emily Thornberry appointed International Trade Secretary in Keir Starmer shadow cabinet|website=Islington Tribune|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n\n===Affordable housing===\n[[File:Yvette Cooper Meeting.jpg|thumb|Thornberry, Corbyn and local councillors present [[Yvette Cooper]] with a petition from Islington residents for more affordable housing, 19 October 2006]]\nThornberry's constituency falls within the [[London Borough of Islington]], one of the most deprived areas of the country with disproportionately high house prices and private sector rents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonpropertywatch.co.uk/average_rental_prices.html |title=London Property Watch |publisher=London Property Watch |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711034848/http://www.londonpropertywatch.co.uk/average_rental_prices.html |archivedate=11 July 2016  }}</ref> She has supported measures by Islington Council to free up under-occupied homes by supporting tenants to downsize<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2013/nov/emily-thornberry-%E2%80%98make-it-easier-elderly-downsize%E2%80%99|title=Emily Thornberry: 'Make it easier for elderly to downsize'|date=15 November 2013|work=Islington Tribune|accessdate=19 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206184119/http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2013/nov/emily-thornberry-%E2%80%98make-it-easier-elderly-downsize%E2%80%99|archivedate=6 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and to stop foreign investors from buying new homes and leaving them empty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm140205/halltext/140205h0001.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 05 Feb 2014 (pt 0001)|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> She has also called for a greater degree of control over private sector rents and more support for social house-building.<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm150304/halltext/150304h0001.htm#150304h0001.htm_spnew6|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 04 Mar 2015 (pt 0001)|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Thornberry has frequently campaigned for a greater commitment to affordable and social housing.<ref name=\"teleprofile\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/11244952/Profile-Emily-Thornberry.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Tom | last=Brooks-Pollock | title=Profile: Emily Thornberry | date=21 November 2014}}</ref> She was criticised when the local ''[[Islington Tribune]]'' newspaper discovered that her husband had bought a former social house which was being rented out to her aides.<ref name=\"teleprofile\" /><ref name=\"thecnj2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecnj.com/islington/2007/083107/news083107_02.html |title=Islington Tribune \u2013 News: auction |publisher=Thecnj.com |date=31 August 2007 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Thornberry said the purchase was \"not about property speculation\".<ref name=\"thecnj2007\" />\n\nIn 2015 Thornberry clashed with [[Boris Johnson]], the mayor of London, over the proposed redevelopments of the [[Mount Pleasant Mail Centre]], the sorting office run by the Royal Mail, and the Clerkenwell Fire Station, both in her constituency.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim |last=Clark |url=http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/mp-decision-on-mt-pleasant-should-be-stripped-from-mayor/8665505.article |title=MP: 'Decision on Mt Pleasant should be stripped from mayor' |work=Architects Journal |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Camden and Islington councils sought to require a high proportion of the resulting new homes to be made available for social rent, but Johnson overturned this and allowed homes designated as \"affordable\" to charge rents of up to 80 percent of market rates. Thornberry criticised Johnson, describing his definition of affordability as \"nonsense\", and called for at least 50% of homes in the new developments to be made available for social rent.<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\" />\n\n===Statue of Emily Davison===\nIn 2013, the 100th anniversary of the death of the suffragette [[Emily Davison]], Thornberry called for a statue commemorating Davison in Parliament.  She arranged a public meeting to discuss options for a memorial, attended by around 800 people, and settled on the idea of a statue as an appropriate memorial, pointing out that there were very few statues of female politicians and activists in Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jun/04/mps-statue-emily-davison-parliament |title=MPs call for statue of Emily Davison in parliament|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Equal pay===\nIn March 2015, Thornberry launched a campaign for a new Equal Pay Act. She said that, 45 years after the original [[Equal Pay Act 1970|Equal Pay Act]] was passed in 1970, women still earned 19% less than men on average.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/08/emily-thornberry-equal-pay-act-overhaul |title=45 years after the Equal Pay Act, there's still a long way to go}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThornberry has lived in [[Islington]] since the early 1990s. In July 1991 she married fellow barrister [[Christopher Nugee]], of Wilberforce Chambers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wilberforce.co.uk/barrister-profiles/christopher-nugee-qc.asp |title=Barristers |publisher=Wilberforce |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009184531/http://www.wilberforce.co.uk/barrister-profiles/christopher-nugee-qc.asp |archivedate=9 October 2011  }}</ref> in [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], and they have two sons and a daughter. Nugee later became a [[Queen's Counsel]], then a [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court Judge]], when he was [[knight]]ed, at which point Thornberry became entitled to be styled Lady Nugee, although she does not use the title. Since 1993 they have lived on Richmond Crescent, [[Barnsbury]], where [[Tony Blair]] also lived until the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], moving in on the same day as the Blairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2010/4/22/islington-south-and-finsbury-liberals-are-irr |title=Islington South and Finsbury \u2013 Liberals are irrelevant, says Labour MP |publisher=politics.co.uk |date=22 April 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Thornberry also part-owns properties in [[Guildford]] and South London;<ref name=\"thecnj2007\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35925.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Democracy Live \u2013 Your representatives \u2013 Emily Thornberry}}</ref> her property portfolio \"is believed to be worth \u00a34.6 million.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/12/18/sir-keir-starmers-wikipedia-page-edited-ahead-expected-labour/ |title=Sir Keir Starmer's Wikipedia page edited to remove reference to his being a 'millionaire' |work=Daily Telegraph |date=18 December 2019 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2005, it was reported that Thornberry had sent her son to the partially selective [[Dame Alice Owen's School|Dame Alice Owen's]] state school {{convert|14|mi|km}} from her home and outside her constituency. The school was formerly based in Islington and still reserves ten per cent of its places for Islington pupils.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.damealiceowens.herts.sch.uk/admissions/ |title=Dame Alice Owen's School \u2013 Admissions |publisher=Damealiceowens.herts.sch.uk |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> The Labour Party opposes selection and Thornberry was widely criticised over the issue as a result.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/3616514/Hypocrisy-at-the-heart-of-Labours-education-policy.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Hypocrisy at the heart of Labour's education policy | date=28 April 2005}}</ref> [[Chris Woodhead]], the former chief inspector of schools, said: \"I celebrate her good sense as a parent and deplore her [[hypocrisy]] as a politician. When will those who espouse the virtues of [[comprehensive education]] apply the logic of their political message to their children?\" Later, Thornberry's daughter attended the same school.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/columnists/janet-street-porter/janet-streetporter-13-years-on-whos-the-heir-to-blairs-lair-1953560.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Janet Street-Porter: 13 years on: Who's the heir to Blair's lair? | date=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official|emilythornberry.com}}\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=emily-thornberry/1536 |hansardcurr=4821 |publicwhip=Emily_Thornberry |theywork=emily_thornberry}}\n* [http://www.islingtonlabour.org.uk Islington South & Finsbury Labour Party]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130603192523/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/t/24185/Emily+THORNBERRY.aspx Debretts People of Today]\n\n===Audio clips===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070803004453/http://www.wpradio.co.uk/mp3s/EmilyThornberryMPinterview.mp3 Women's Parliamentary Radio] Online audio interview discussing her life as a female MP\n\n===News items===\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/1996685/Politics-Could-Islington-be-the-home-of-the-two-mother-family.html Defending two mother families in May 2008]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160111024523/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2010/may/local-elections-2010-labour-victory-party-showed-fighting-spirit Camden New Journal]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patricia Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal|The Baroness Scotland of Asthal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Willy Bach, Baron Bach|The Lord Bach]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence]]|years=2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hilary Benn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Foreign Secretary]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lisa Nandy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]|years=2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Keir Starmer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Angela Eagle]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow First Secretary of State]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Angela Rayner]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry Gardiner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Shadow Foreign Secretaries}}\n{{Shadow Great Officers of State}}\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Shadow Defence Secretaries}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2020}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thornberry, Emily}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Kent]]\n[[Category:Members of Gray's Inn]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Guildford]]\n[[Category:Politics of the London Borough of Islington]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Wives of knights]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = Emily Thornberry\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Emily Thornberry MP crop 2.jpg\n|caption = Thornberry in January 2020\n|office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade|Shadow Secretary of State<br>for International Trade]]\n|leader = [[Keir Starmer]]\n|term_start = 6 April 2020\n|predecessor = [[Barry Gardiner]]\n|office1 = [[Shadow First Secretary of State]]\n|leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start1 = 14 June 2017\n|term_end1 = 5 April 2020\n|predecessor1 = [[Angela Eagle]] (2016)\n|successor1  = [[Angela Rayner]]\n|office2 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]\n|leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start2 = 27 June 2016\n|term_end2 = 5 April 2020\n|predecessor2 = [[Hilary Benn]]\n|successor2 = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n|office3 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n|leader3 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start3 = 20 July 2016\n|term_end3 = 6 October 2016\n|predecessor3 = ''Position established''\n|successor3 = [[Keir Starmer]]\n|office4 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence]]\n|leader4 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start4 = 5 January 2016\n|term_end4 = 27 June 2016\n|predecessor4 = [[Maria Eagle]]\n|successor4 = [[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]]\n|office5 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow Minister of State for Employment]]\n|leader5 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start5 = 16 September 2015\n|term_end5 = 6 January 2016\n|predecessor5 = [[Stephen Timms]]\n|successor5 = [[Nick Thomas-Symonds]]\n|office6 = [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]]\n|leader6 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start6 = 7 October 2011\n|term_end6 = 3 December 2014\n|predecessor6 = [[Patricia Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal|The Baroness Scotland of Asthal]]\n|successor6 = [[Willy Bach, Baron Bach|The Lord Bach]]\n|office8 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]]\n|term_start8 = 6 May 2005\n|term_end8 =\n|predecessor8 = [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]]\n|successor8 = \n|majority8 = 17,328 (36.3%)\n|birth_name=Emily Anne Thornberry\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1960|7|27}}\n|birth_place = [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]], England\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Christopher Nugee]]|July 1991}}\n|children = 3\n|parents = [[Cedric Thornberry]]<br />Sallie Thornberry\n|alma_mater = [[University of Kent]]\n|website = {{official|emilythornberry.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Emily Anne Thornberry''' (born 27 July 1960) is a [[British people|British]] [[politician]] who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]] since [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], she served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Shadow First Secretary of State]] from 2017 to 2020 and [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]] from 2016 to 2020. \n\nThornberry practised as a [[barrister]] from 1985 to 2005. She was first elected to Parliament in 2005, and served as [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]] in [[Ed Miliband]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband|shadow cabinet]] from 2011 until she resigned in 2014 after sending a tweet that was described as \"snobby\". After [[Jeremy Corbyn]] won the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 leadership election]], Thornberry was appointed [[Department for Work and Pensions|shadow employment minister]]. In [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn#January 2016 reshuffle|January 2016]], she was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence|Shadow Defence Secretary]], and in [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn#June 2016 reshuffle|June 2016]] she was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]]. She was a candidate to succeed [[Jeremy Corbyn|Corbyn]] as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]] in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020 leadership election]]. She was appointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet of Keir Starmer]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade|Shadow International Trade Secretary]] in April 2020, succeeding [[Barry Gardiner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/press/keir-starmer-announces-senior-shadow-cabinet-appointments/|title=Keir Starmer announces senior Shadow Cabinet appointments|website=[[The Labour Party (UK)| The Labour Party]]|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThornberry was born in [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]] on 27 July 1960.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-45759|title=Thornberry, Rt Hon. Emily, (born 27 July 1960), PC 2016; MP (Lab) Islington South and Finsbury, since 2005 {{!}} WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO|website=www.ukwhoswho.com|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U45759|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a3055464-b54f-11e8-bbc3-ccd7de085ffe|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> Her parents were Sallie Thornberry, a teacher, and [[Cedric Thornberry]], at the time teaching international law at the [[London School of Economics]], and later a [[Assistant Secretary-General|United Nations Assistant Secretary-General]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/21/emily-thornberry-profile-labour-mp-islington|title=Emily Thornberry: Guildford girl who went on to become a devoted MP|last=Johnston|first=Chris|date=21 November 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iww8h3E8MBMC&pg=PA719&lpg=PA719&dq=cederic+thornberry+UN+nato#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The UN Security Council: From the Cold War to the 21st Century \u2013 David Malone |accessdate=20 June 2012|isbn=9781588262400 |last1=Malone |first1=David |last2=Malone |first2=Rector David M. |year=2004 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/01/cedric-thornberry|title=Cedric Thornberry obituary|last=Ahtisaari|first=Martti|date=1 June 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> When Thornberry was seven, her parents divorced and she had to leave their home with her mother and two brothers. After this, she relied on free school meals and food parcels, and their cats were euthanised to save money.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/25/emily-thornberry-labour-hope-have-election|title=Emily Thornberry: 'I hope we have an election before any more damage is done'|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|date=25 November 2017|website=The Guardian|accessdate=}}</ref> Her mother later became a Labour [[councillor]] and mayor, and her father stood as the Labour candidate for [[Guildford (UK Parliament constituency)|Guildford]] in the [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966 general election]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Aida | last=Edemariam | title=Right, so just what do you do all day? | date=19 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nShe failed the [[eleven-plus]] exam, so attended a [[secondary modern school]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She left to live with her father when she was fifteen until he left without warning to work for the [[United Nations]] when she was seventeen. She worked as a cleaner and a barmaid in London alongside resitting her [[O-Levels]] and taking her [[A-Levels]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/21/emily-thornberry-interview-labour-antisemitism-brexit-chippy|title=Emily Thornberry: 'Being chippy is a good thing'|last=Cooke|first=Rachel|date=21 July 2019|work=The Observer|accessdate=21 July 2019|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> She went on to study law at the [[University of Kent]] in [[Canterbury]], graduating in 1982. She was called to the Bar at [[Gray's Inn]] and practised as a barrister specialising in human rights law from 1985 to 2005 under [[Michael Mansfield]] at Tooks Chambers.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThornberry joined the [[Transport and General Workers' Union]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XhMWAQAAIAAJ&q=%22emily+thornberry%22+1960&dq=%22emily+thornberry%22+1960 |title=Dod's parliamentary companion guide to the general election, 2005 \u2013 Valerie Passmore, David Roe |accessdate=20 June 2012|isbn=9780905702575 |last1=Passmore |first1=Valerie |year=2005 }}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Before Parliament ===\nIn the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], she stood as the Labour candidate in [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]], but was defeated by the Conservative incumbent, [[Julian Brazier]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/constituency/788/canterbury|title=Canterbury: Constituency|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 June 2012|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the decision of [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]] not to stand again, Thornberry was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]] for the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] through an [[All-women shortlists|all-women shortlist]] of prospective candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf|title=Standard Note SN/PC/05057|work=House of Commons Library|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618162209/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf|archivedate=18 June 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref> She was elected to Parliament with a majority of 484.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/341.stm|title=Election 2005 \u2013 Islington South & Finsbury|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> [[Nick Smith (British politician)|Nick Smith]] (who subsequently was elected to Parliament representing [[Blaenau Gwent (UK Parliament constituency)|Blaenau Gwent]]) served as her election agent.\n\n===Early Parliamentary career (2005\u20132010)===\nThornberry made her [[maiden speech]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 24 May 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo050524/debtext/50524-26.htm#50524-26_spnew0 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 24 May 2005 (pt 26) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=24 May 2005 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> In Parliament, she has been a member of the Environmental Audit Committee and was on the [[Communities and Local Government Committee|Communities and Local Government Select Committee]] during the 2005\u201310 Parliament. She has served as vice-chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Cycling Group and the All-Party Parliamentary Pro-Choice and Sexual Health Group.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn 2006, Thornberry was criticised by the Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards [[Philip Mawer]] for adding a quote from herself into a news release by the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]]. She was found not to have broken the Parliamentary code of conduct.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7062530.stm|title=MP 'unwise' to alter news release|date=29 October 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThornberry's main interests since becoming an MP have been in health, housing, the environment and equality.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-35234485|title=Emily Thornberry: Comeback queen|last=Wheeler|first=Brian|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> She has also spoken on the need for more affordable housing, particularly in [[Islington]]. In 2006, Thornberry introduced the Housing Association Bill, a [[Private Member's Bill]] which sought to improve the control of housing association tenants over their landlords.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmbills/035/07035.i-5.html |title=Housing Association (Rights and Representation of Residents) Bill |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=28 February 2007 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Many of the ideas from this bill were taken up by the Cave Review.<ref>[http://www.communities.gov.uk/housing/strategiesandreviews/cavereview1 Cave Review] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081114124338/http://www.communities.gov.uk/housing/strategiesandreviews/cavereview1 |date=14 November 2008 }}</ref> On environmental matters, Thornberry worked with [[Friends of the Earth]] and [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) to campaign for a Climate Change Bill and a Marine Bill. In 2006, Thornberry won the ePolitix Award for Environment Champion of the Year after being nominated by WWF.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ecca.org.uk/charity_champion_award_2006.doc |accessdate=18 November 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Thornberry supported a change in the law to allow single women and lesbian couples to seek [[in vitro fertilisation]] treatment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7410934.stm|title=MPs reject need for father in IVF|date=20 May 2008|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/fertility-laws-drop-need-to-consider-role-of-father-831544.html|title=Fertility laws drop need to consider role of father|date=21 May 2008|website=The Independent|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she was appointed as a ministerial aide in the [[Department of Energy and Climate Change]] and attended the [[Copenhagen Summit]] in December that year with [[Joan Ruddock]] and [[Ed Miliband]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/news/2010/09/28/climate-change-deal-several-years-away|title=Climate change deal 'several years away'|website=politics.co.uk|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition under Ed Miliband (2010\u20132015)===\n{{See also|Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband}}\nIn May 2010, Thornberry was returned as MP for Islington South and Finsbury with an increased majority, in a seat identified as the Liberal Democrats' top target in England for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/may/election-2010-results-emily-wins-night-jubilant-emily-thornberry-defeats-lib-dem-bridg|title=Jubilant Emily Thornberry defeats Lib Dem Bridget Fox in Islington South & Finsbury|date=7 May 2010|work=Islington Tribune|accessdate=20 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317111337/http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/may/election-2010-results-emily-wins-night-jubilant-emily-thornberry-defeats-lib-dem-bridg|archivedate=17 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/15731364 |title=Election campaigning: A tale of two constituencies |work=The Economist |date= 20 March 2010|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThornberry was promoted to Shadow Minister for the Department of Energy and Climate Change in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/emily-thornberry/1536|title=Emily Thornberry MP|publisher=Parliament UK|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In the role she shadowed [[Charles Hendry]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons, Westminster |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm100708/halltext/100708h0001.htm#10070873000191 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 8 July 2010 (pt 0001) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Thornberry missed out on a place in Labour's [[Shadow Cabinet|shadow cabinet]], then elected by Labour MPs, by one vote. She was instead promoted to the role of shadow care minister under the shadow health secretary [[John Healey (politician)|John Healey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/news/new_job_cheers_mp_emily_thornberry_after_shadow_cabinet_heartbreak_1_682213 |title=New job cheers MP Emily Thornberry after shadow cabinet heartbreak  |work=Islington Gazette |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/oct/emily-thornberry-set-shadow-every-coalition-move-health |title=Emily Thornberry set to shadow every Coalition move on health |work=Islington Tribune |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303120348/http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2010/oct/emily-thornberry-set-shadow-every-coalition-move-health |archivedate=3 March 2012  }}</ref>\n\nAs shadow care minister, Thornberry criticised the coalition government's lack of action over failing care home operator Southern Cross, calling for action and that the government put in place a plan B should the operator fail.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/uk-13611766 |title= Southern Cross: Government tries to reassure residents |publisher= BBC News|date= 1 June 2011|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> She criticised the government over the Winterborne View care home abuse scandal, calling for an investigation into the affair.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/jun/07/ed-miliband-talks-future-social-care |title=Government could order independent inquiry into Winterbourne View|work=The Guardian |date=7 June 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |location=London |first=Helene |last=Mulholland}}</ref> In April 2011, Thornberry surveyed all the local government directors of adult social care and highlighted the pressures on care for the elderly by the coalition government's cuts to local authority funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coalitionwatch.info/2011/04/crisis-of-care-predicted-by-labour.html |title=Coalition watch |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129095502/http://www.coalitionwatch.info/2011/04/crisis-of-care-predicted-by-labour.html |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThornberry was appointed [[Shadow Attorney General|shadow attorney general]] in October 2011, in which capacity she attended shadow cabinet meetings.<ref name=\"parliament1\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201212/cmhansrd/cm120320/debtext/120320-0001.htm#12032051001266 |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 20 Mar 2012 (pt 0001) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Thornberry called for action by [[Dominic Grieve]] over [[Applied Language Solutions]]' failure to provide interpreters for court proceedings,<ref>{{cite news|first=Owen |last=Bowcott|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2012/mar/19/private-court-interpretation-contractor-contempt |title=Private court interpretation company 'should face contempt proceedings |work=The Guardian |date= 19 March 2012|accessdate=20 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref> and called on the attorney general to ensure that allegations of bribery involving [[Bernie Ecclestone]] were properly investigated.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn 2011, Thornberry challenged [[David Cameron]] over his false claims about wages at Islington Council,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2011/jul/still-no-apology-prime-minister-david-cameron-salary-%E2%80%98lie%E2%80%99 |title=Still no apology from Prime Minister David Cameron for salary 'lie' |work=Camden New Journal |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111024523/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2011/jul/still-no-apology-prime-minister-david-cameron-salary-%E2%80%98lie%E2%80%99 |archivedate=11 January 2016  }}</ref> campaigning against government measures which Thornberry claimed to have exacerbated child poverty in Islington,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emilythornberry.com/news/53/17/New-figures-reveal-Islington-suffers-second-worst-child-poverty-in-the-UK |title=News Emily Thornberry is the Labour MP for Islington South & Finsbury and Shadow Health & Social Care Minister |publisher=emilythornberry.com |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219070849/http://www.emilythornberry.com/news/53/17/New-figures-reveal-Islington-suffers-second-worst-child-poverty-in-the-UK |archivedate=19 February 2012 }}</ref> and answering over 1,000 enquiries a month from constituents.<ref name=\"Edemariam\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Aida | last=Edemariam | title=Right, so just what do you do all day? | date=19 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nThornberry resigned her shadow cabinet position on 20 November 2014, shortly after polls closed in the [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|Rochester and Strood by-election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30139832|title=Labour's Emily Thornberry quits over 'snobby' tweet|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/20/emily-thornberry-resigns-rochester-tweet-labour-shadow-cabinet|title=Emily Thornberry resigns from shadow cabinet over Rochester tweet|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2014}}</ref> Earlier in the day, she had received criticism after [[tweeting]] a photograph of a house in the constituency adorned with three [[Flag of England|flags of St. George]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30139832 |title=Labour's Emily Thornberry quits over 'snobby' tweet \u2013 BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=21 November 2014 |accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> and the owner's [[white van man|white van]] parked outside on the driveway, under the caption \"Image from #Rochester\", provoking accusations of [[snob]]bery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30139832|title=Labour's Emily Thornberry quits over tweet|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 November 2014 |publisher=BBC News | accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> She was criticised by fellow Labour Party MPs, including leader [[Ed Miliband]] who said her tweet conveyed a \"sense of disrespect\", [[Chris Bryant]] who said that it broke the \"first rule of politics\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30148768|title=Miliband: Thornberry's 'white van, flag' tweet lacked respect|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> and [[Simon Danczuk]] who said that the party had been \"hijacked by the north London [[liberal elite]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30142579|title=Emily Thornberry: How one tweet led to her resignation|date=21 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition under Jeremy Corbyn (2015\u20132020)===\n{{See also|Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn}}\n[[File:Emily Thornberry, 2016 Labour Party Conference 2.jpg|thumb|Thornberry giving her Shadow Foreign Secretary speech at the 2016 Labour Party Conference]]\nIn September 2015, she was appointed as the shadow minister for employment by the new Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\":4\" /> She was promoted to shadow defence secretary in January 2016, replacing [[Maria Eagle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jan/05/hilary-benn-expected-to-keep-his-job-as-corbyn-finishes-shadow-cabinet-reshuffle-politics-live|title=Emily Thornberry named Shadoecretary in Labour reshuffle|last1=Sparrow|first1=Andrew|date=6 January 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Thornberry advocated spending money on the army rather than on the UK's [[Trident (UK nuclear programme)|Trident]] nuclear programme.<ref name=\":4\" /> On being appointed, Thornberry was interviewed by the [[British Forces Broadcasting Service]], where she defended her appointment, saying she had \"quite a lot more experience than people might think.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35248233 |title=Emily Thornberry defends Labour defence appointment |publisher=BBC News |date=6 January 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> During her role as shadow defence secretary, Thornberry conducted a review of defence policy, including the role of the nuclear deterrent, which was delayed following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jan/14/emily-thornberry-final-say-labour-trident-review-nuclear-ken-livingstone|title=Emily Thornberry will have final say on Labour's Trident review|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=14 January 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> During a private Labour discussion about the nuclear deterrent, Thornberry asked what \"[[DEFCON|Defcon]] One\", a status of the United States nuclear defence rating, meant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/03/labours-shadow-defence-secretary-does-not-understand-what-defcon/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Labour's shadow defence secretary 'does not understand what Defcon One means'|accessdate=15 September 2016|date=3 April 2016 |last1=Riley-Smith |first1=Ben }}</ref>\n\nThornberry was promoted to [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]] in June 2016 after Corbyn fired [[Hilary Benn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-36632956|title=Jeremy Corbyn unveils new top team after resignations|date=27 June 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> She held the role of [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow Brexit Secretary]] concurrently until [[Keir Starmer]] took on the role later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/the1000/the-progress-1000-londons-most-influential-people-2016-westminster-a3336621.html|title=The Progress 1000: Westminster|date=7 September 2016|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> She accused Sky News presenter [[Dermot Murnaghan]] of sexism after he asked her to name French [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Development (France)|minister of foreign affairs and international development]], [[Jean-Marc Ayrault]] and the president of South Korea, which she was unable to do.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37332287|title=Thornberry accuses presenter of 'sexism'|date=11 September 2016|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/11/emily-thornberry-sexism-dermot-murnaghan-sky-news|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Sky presenter Murnaghan of sexism|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|date=11 September 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/11/emily-thornberry-accuses-sky-news-presenter-of-sexism-after-fail/|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Sky News presenter Dermot Murnaghan of 'sexism' after failing to name French foreign minister|last=Hughes|first=Laura|date=11 September 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Following the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], she was given the additional role of [[Shadow First Secretary of State|Shadow First Secretary of State]], effectively acting as Corbyn's number 2. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/emily-thornberry-interview-i-do-have-a-go-at-boris-weve-lost-status-people-laugh-at-us-now-ff6056d5z|title=Emily Thornberry interview: 'I do have a go at Boris. We've lost status \u2014 people laugh at us now'|last=Fisher|first=Lucy|date=23 December 2017|work=The Times|accessdate=22 July 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nThornberry opposed Britain's involvement in the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]] against the [[Shia]] [[Houthis]]. She said that \"while Saudi Arabia will remain a valued [[Saudi Arabia\u2013United Kingdom relations|strategic, security and economic ally]] in the years to come, our support for their forces in Yemen must be suspended until the alleged violations of international humanitarian law in that conflict have been fully and independently investigated.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour MPs face backlash over failure to vote on Yemen campaign |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/27/labour-mps-face-backlash-over-failure-to-vote-on-yemen-campaign |last=Mason |first=Rowena |work=The Guardian |date=27 October 2016}}</ref> In May 2018 Thornberry said support in [[Syria]] for the country's president, [[Bashar al-Assad]], had been \u201cunderestimated\u201d in the West.<ref>{{cite web|first=Samuel |last=Osborne |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/assad-syria-emily-thornberry-support-underestimated-jeremy-corbyn-russia-a8355241.html |title=Emily Thornberry claims public support for Syria's Bashar al-Assad has been 'underestimated' |work=The Independent |date= 17 May 2018|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Foster |first=Matt |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/world/middle-east/news/95218/emily-thornberry-bashar-al-assads-popularity-syria-has-been |title=Emily Thornberry: Bashar al-Assad's popularity in Syria has been 'underestimated' |publisher=PoliticsHome.com |date=16 May 2018|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> In October 2018 Thornberry criticised [[Theresa May]]'s government's response to [[Jamal Khashoggi]]'s disappearance as \"too little, too late\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi: Labour slams government's response as 'too little, too late'. |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/13/labour-slams-government-over-khashoggi-response-emily-thornberry |last=Graham-Harrison |first=Emma |work=The Guardian |date=13 October 2018}}</ref> She said: \"Imagine how this government would have reacted if either Russia or Iran had abducted\u2013and in all likelihood murdered\u2013one of their dissident journalists within the sovereign territory of another country.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=European Governments Wrestle with Khashoggi Quandary |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/european-governments-wrestle-with-khashoggi-quandary/4617229.html |work=VOA News |date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Corbyn announced he was stepping down as leader, Thornberry was the first person to officially announce that she would be running for leader of the Labour Party, in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020 leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/thornberry-first-to-enter-labour-leadership-race-after-election-defeat|title=Thornberry first to enter Labour leadership race after election defeat|last=Bates|first=Liz|website=Channel 4 News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the week after the election, defeated Labour MP [[Caroline Flint]] appeared on ''[[Sophy Ridge on Sunday]]'' and accused Thornberry of saying that Brexit voters in [[Northern England]] were 'stupid'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/|title=Yorkshire Post - Yorkshire News|website=Yorkshire Post|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Thornberry appeared on [[ITV News|''ITV News'']] and accused Flint of 'making up shit about her' and threatened to take [[legal action]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-15/thornberry-criticises-total-and-utter-lie-shared-by-labour-colleague/|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Caroline Flint of 'making up s***' about her and says she is taking legal action|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/16/emily-thornberry-threatens-to-sue-over-caroline-flint-stupid-voters-claim|title=Emily Thornberry threatens to sue over 'stupid voters' claim|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=2019-12-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She was eventually eliminated from the leadership election after failing to achieve enough nominations from the party's MPs and MEPs.\n\nAfter the killing of [[Qasem Soleimani]] in the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike]], Thornberry condemned the actions of the [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]]. She said that she shed no tears over the death, but was fearful of escalating tensions in the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/05/boris-johnson-qassem-suleimani-was-threat-to-all-our-interests-lament-death|title=Boris Johnson: Qassem Suleimani was threat to all our interests|last=editor|first=Heather Stewart Political|date=2020-01-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition under Keir Starmer (2020\u2013present)===\n{{See also|Shadow Cabinet of Keir Starmer}}\nThornberry was replaced as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]] by [[Lisa Nandy]] upon the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|election]] of [[Keir Starmer]] as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52175841|title=Lisa Nandy appointed shadow foreign secretary|date=2020-04-05|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/indianorigin-british-mp-lisa-nandy-promises-constructive-opposition-as-uk-shadow-minister/1793588|title=Indian-origin British MP Lisa Nandy promises constructive Opposition as UK shadow minister|last=|first=|date=|website=outlookindia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Thornberry herself was not sacked from the [[Official Opposition frontbench]], but instead moved to a lower-ranking frontbench role, becoming the new [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]. She replaced [[Barry Gardiner]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/news/emily-thornberry-appointed-as-shadow-international-trade-secretary-1-6595958|title=Emily Thornberry appointed as shadow international trade secretary|last=Cumiskey|first=Lucas|website=Islington Gazette|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and said on [[Twitter]] that, \"It's been a pleasure to work with Barry Gardiner these past four years... I hope I can take the fight to the government on [[International trade|International Trade]] as effectively as he did, and I'll be very lucky to have his advice\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://islingtontribune.com/article/emily-thornberry-appointed-international-trade-secretary-in-keir-starmer-shadow-cabinet|title=Emily Thornberry appointed International Trade Secretary in Keir Starmer shadow cabinet|website=Islington Tribune|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n\n===Affordable housing===\n[[File:Yvette Cooper Meeting.jpg|thumb|Thornberry, Corbyn and local councillors present [[Yvette Cooper]] with a petition from Islington residents for more affordable housing, 19 October 2006]]\nThornberry's constituency falls within the [[London Borough of Islington]], one of the most deprived areas of the country with disproportionately high house prices and private sector rents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonpropertywatch.co.uk/average_rental_prices.html |title=London Property Watch |publisher=London Property Watch |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711034848/http://www.londonpropertywatch.co.uk/average_rental_prices.html |archivedate=11 July 2016  }}</ref> She has supported measures by Islington Council to free up under-occupied homes by supporting tenants to downsize<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2013/nov/emily-thornberry-%E2%80%98make-it-easier-elderly-downsize%E2%80%99|title=Emily Thornberry: 'Make it easier for elderly to downsize'|date=15 November 2013|work=Islington Tribune|accessdate=19 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206184119/http://www.islingtontribune.com/news/2013/nov/emily-thornberry-%E2%80%98make-it-easier-elderly-downsize%E2%80%99|archivedate=6 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and to stop foreign investors from buying new homes and leaving them empty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm140205/halltext/140205h0001.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 05 Feb 2014 (pt 0001)|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> She has also called for a greater degree of control over private sector rents and more support for social house-building.<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm150304/halltext/150304h0001.htm#150304h0001.htm_spnew6|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 04 Mar 2015 (pt 0001)|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Thornberry has frequently campaigned for a greater commitment to affordable and social housing.<ref name=\"teleprofile\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/11244952/Profile-Emily-Thornberry.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Tom | last=Brooks-Pollock | title=Profile: Emily Thornberry | date=21 November 2014}}</ref> She was criticised when the local ''[[Islington Tribune]]'' newspaper discovered that her husband had bought a former social house which was being rented out to her aides.<ref name=\"teleprofile\" /><ref name=\"thecnj2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecnj.com/islington/2007/083107/news083107_02.html |title=Islington Tribune \u2013 News: auction |publisher=Thecnj.com |date=31 August 2007 |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Thornberry said the purchase was \"not about property speculation\".<ref name=\"thecnj2007\" />\n\nIn 2015 Thornberry clashed with [[Boris Johnson]], the mayor of London, over the proposed redevelopments of the [[Mount Pleasant Mail Centre]], the sorting office run by the Royal Mail, and the Clerkenwell Fire Station, both in her constituency.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim |last=Clark |url=http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/mp-decision-on-mt-pleasant-should-be-stripped-from-mayor/8665505.article |title=MP: 'Decision on Mt Pleasant should be stripped from mayor' |work=Architects Journal |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Camden and Islington councils sought to require a high proportion of the resulting new homes to be made available for social rent, but Johnson overturned this and allowed homes designated as \"affordable\" to charge rents of up to 80 percent of market rates. Thornberry criticised Johnson, describing his definition of affordability as \"nonsense\", and called for at least 50% of homes in the new developments to be made available for social rent.<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\" />\n\n===Statue of Emily Davison===\nIn 2013, the 100th anniversary of the death of the suffragette [[Emily Davison]], Thornberry called for a statue commemorating Davison in Parliament.  She arranged a public meeting to discuss options for a memorial, attended by around 800 people, and settled on the idea of a statue as an appropriate memorial, pointing out that there were very few statues of female politicians and activists in Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jun/04/mps-statue-emily-davison-parliament |title=MPs call for statue of Emily Davison in parliament|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Equal pay===\nIn March 2015, Thornberry launched a campaign for a new Equal Pay Act. She said that, 45 years after the original [[Equal Pay Act 1970|Equal Pay Act]] was passed in 1970, women still earned 19% less than men on average.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/08/emily-thornberry-equal-pay-act-overhaul |title=45 years after the Equal Pay Act, there's still a long way to go}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThornberry has lived in [[Islington]] since the early 1990s. In July 1991 she married fellow barrister [[Christopher Nugee]], of Wilberforce Chambers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wilberforce.co.uk/barrister-profiles/christopher-nugee-qc.asp |title=Barristers |publisher=Wilberforce |accessdate=20 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009184531/http://www.wilberforce.co.uk/barrister-profiles/christopher-nugee-qc.asp |archivedate=9 October 2011  }}</ref> in [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], and they have two sons and a daughter. Nugee later became a [[Queen's Counsel]], then a [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court Judge]], when he was [[knight]]ed, at which point Thornberry became entitled to be styled Lady Nugee, although she does not use the title. Since 1993 they have lived on Richmond Crescent, [[Barnsbury]], where [[Tony Blair]] also lived until the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], moving in on the same day as the Blairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2010/4/22/islington-south-and-finsbury-liberals-are-irr |title=Islington South and Finsbury \u2013 Liberals are irrelevant, says Labour MP |publisher=politics.co.uk |date=22 April 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Thornberry also part-owns properties in [[Guildford]] and South London;<ref name=\"thecnj2007\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35925.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Democracy Live \u2013 Your representatives \u2013 Emily Thornberry}}</ref> her property portfolio \"is believed to be worth \u00a34.6 million.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/12/18/sir-keir-starmers-wikipedia-page-edited-ahead-expected-labour/ |title=Sir Keir Starmer's Wikipedia page edited to remove reference to his being a 'millionaire' |work=Daily Telegraph |date=18 December 2019 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2005, it was reported that Thornberry had sent her son to the partially selective [[Dame Alice Owen's School|Dame Alice Owen's]] state school {{convert|14|mi|km}} from her home and outside her constituency. The school was formerly based in Islington and still reserves ten per cent of its places for Islington pupils.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.damealiceowens.herts.sch.uk/admissions/ |title=Dame Alice Owen's School \u2013 Admissions |publisher=Damealiceowens.herts.sch.uk |accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> The Labour Party opposes selection and Thornberry was widely criticised over the issue as a result.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/3616514/Hypocrisy-at-the-heart-of-Labours-education-policy.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Hypocrisy at the heart of Labour's education policy | date=28 April 2005}}</ref> [[Chris Woodhead]], the former chief inspector of schools, said: \"I celebrate her good sense as a parent and deplore her [[hypocrisy]] as a politician. When will those who espouse the virtues of [[comprehensive education]] apply the logic of their political message to their children?\" Later, Thornberry's daughter attended the same school.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/columnists/janet-street-porter/janet-streetporter-13-years-on-whos-the-heir-to-blairs-lair-1953560.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Janet Street-Porter: 13 years on: Who's the heir to Blair's lair? | date=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official|emilythornberry.com}}\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=emily-thornberry/1536 |hansardcurr=4821 |publicwhip=Emily_Thornberry |theywork=emily_thornberry}}\n* [http://www.islingtonlabour.org.uk Islington South & Finsbury Labour Party]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130603192523/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/t/24185/Emily+THORNBERRY.aspx Debretts People of Today]\n\n===Audio clips===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070803004453/http://www.wpradio.co.uk/mp3s/EmilyThornberryMPinterview.mp3 Women's Parliamentary Radio] Online audio interview discussing her life as a female MP\n\n===News items===\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/1996685/Politics-Could-Islington-be-the-home-of-the-two-mother-family.html Defending two mother families in May 2008]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160111024523/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2010/may/local-elections-2010-labour-victory-party-showed-fighting-spirit Camden New Journal]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Islington South and Finsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Islington South and Finsbury]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patricia Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal|The Baroness Scotland of Asthal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Willy Bach, Baron Bach|The Lord Bach]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Sec